@node int "LChecker 2.1 Amigaguide Document"

   LChecker is a handy little utility to quickly check your lottery numbers
every week.  It has a nice 8 Colour interface (MWB) and can store up to 50
rows of numbers (as Tooltypes).  It also has a very useful AutoStart function
so that you don't have to wait for your Amiga to boot up in order to check
your numbers.  I included this because LC is meant as a time-saving utility,
but if you had to wait ages after each draw before using it, then it would be
defeating the object!  Hmmm, you do have to be a little careful when using
AutoStart though, so read 'Usage-AutoStart' first.  Don't worry, it won't
wipe your HD or anything, but you may find that LC doesn't start when you
want it to, and starts when you don't, if you don't follow the instructions
carefully.
   I have made LC GIFTWARE because I put a fair amount of work into it, but it
isn't an essential addition to your HardDrive.  Just send me a choccy bar or
something.  Hey, if you win the lottery, why not go mad and send me an A/Box :)
   Can I also plug MadHouse here, please?  Thankyou!  I think that everyone
should get a copy of this off Aminet (where else!) and then...(SHOCK)...
register it!!  It really is THE BEST screensaver around and well worth the $15.
I registered, and got a very nice letter back, along with a great piece of
software.  Look, just try it out okay, and see if you don't fall in love with
the wonderful interface (MUI), beautiful Dimmer function (select the Dim colour!),
vast array of options (musical blankers anyone?) and, of course, the World Famous
(well, it should be :) Stars blanker (shifts, turns, reverse...)!  Furthermore,
you can also import other blanker types into MadHouse too!  Go on, try it out...
(And no, the authors aren't paying me to say this)

 @{"-> Installation" Link ins}
@endnode
@node ins "LChecker 2.1 Amigaguide Document"

   Before using LChecker, it is recommended that you use MWB colours, and have
the XCourier.font installed (not included).  Otherwise, things won't be as pretty
as they should be.

   Okay then, are you ready for this:

   1: Make a drawer for LChecker.
   2: Copy LChecker2.1 to this drawer.
   3: Copy LChecker2.1.info to this drawer.
   4: Copy LC2.S to this drawer.
   5: ...er...
   6: That's it!
   7: No, really.
   8: I'm serious!!

   Even easier, when you unpack the LChecker.LHA archive, a nice drawer will be
created for you, with all of the files in it!

   There are actually a couple of rules to follow.  Firstly, LChecker MUST have
an icon.  Secondly, you can rename the LChecker program, but DO NOT rename LC2.S!
Finally, keep LC2.S in the same drawer as LChecker2.1.  If you fail to do any of
this then LChecker will inform you, and then quit.  Can you handle all that?
Good!  Now, go play with LC...

 @{"->   Using LC  " Link use}
@endnode
@node use "LChecker 2.1 Amigaguide Document"

   To run LChecker you will need WB 2.0+, as this program uses Tooltypes and
ASL Requestors.  But surely no-one has WB 1.3....?! :)  You should also use MWB
colours, and have XHelvetica.font installed (not included).
   LChecker uses the English Lottery format. ie: 6 Balls and a Bonus Ball are
drawn.  Match 3,4,5,5+BB or 6 numbers to win some cash.  Draw takes place
weekly.  I think that this is pretty much the standard format...?!
   Click on a button:

 @{"  Useful Diagram  " Link u-dgm}

 @{"Enter Your Numbers" Link u-ent}
 @{"Enter Lottery Nums" Link u-lot}

 @{"  LC Preferences  " Link u-prf}
 @{"AutoStart Function" Link u-ats}
 @{"Keyboard ShortCuts" Link u-kbs}

 @{"  Tooltypes List  " Link u-ttl}
 @{"  Error Messages  " Link u-erm}
@endnode
