@node u-ent "LChecker 2.1 Amigaguide Document"

   After loading LC, you will first need to enter your own weekly numbers.  To
do this check that LC is in Alter mode:

   @{b}If there is a cross next to the 'Alter' button, then click on 'Alter'.
@{ub}
   Now look at the box in the bottom left.  This tells you the current row
number.  Now move to whichever row number you want to change.  LC can store 50
different rows!

   @{b}Press the arrow gadgets to scroll up and down the rows.  Click on the left
   hand column of (!) buttons to quickly select a visible row.
@{ub}
   Now enter one of your rows of numbers into LCheckers database, using the
49 'ball' gadgets on the right:

   @{b}Click on the 6 numbered balls that represent your line.  They will appear in
   the selected row on the left of the screen.
@{ub}
   Repeat this process for all of your lines.  Now click on 'Save' to save your
lines as Tooltypes in LChecker's icon.

   NOTE: If you click on the 'Alter' button while in 'Alter' mode, a set of
         random numbers will be entered for you.

 @{"-> Enter Lottery Nums" Link u-lot}        @{"->  Diagram " Link u-dgm}
@endnode
@node u-lot "LChecker 2.1 Amigaguide Document"

   Make Sure that you are in 'Check' mode.  It might also be a good idea if you
have @{"Entered Some Lines" Link u-ent} beforehand :)

   @{b}If there is a cross next to the 'Check' button, then click on 'Check'.
@{ub}
   Now you should enter the six winning Lottery Numbers, using the 49 'ball'
gadgets on the right:

   @{b}Click on the 6 numbered balls that represent the winning Lottery Numbers.
@{ub}
   Now select a seventh 'ball'.  This will represent the winning Bonus Ball for
this weeks numbers.

   @{b}Click on another gadget.  A small 'b' will appear next to it.
@{ub}
   Now scroll through your list of numbers that you entered earlier.  The display
on the right will indicate when one or more balls match, and will give you the
subtotal on the right of each row.  This will be subtley highlighted if you have
three or more matched numbers in a row!!

 @{"->   LC Preferences  " Link u-prf}        @{"->  Diagram " Link u-dgm}

@endnode
@node u-prf "LChecker 2.1 Amigaguide Document"

   LChecker has 5 preferences to alter, changed via the Menu or Tooltypes.

   Workbench: If selected, LC will open its window on the Workbench.  Otherwise,
              it will open its own HiRes Laced screen.  This will be ignored if
              the Workbench screen has too few colours ( Colours<8 ).

   Centre:    If selected, LC will centre its window on the current screen.

   WinX=?:    {Tooltype Only}  This contains the X offset of LC's window.
              Ignored if 'Centre' is set.

   WinY=?:    {Tooltype Only}  Oh, c'mon.  Work it out! :)

   FastQuit:  If selected, LC won't bring up a requester before quitting.

   Note: If you set these preferences via the Menu in LC itself, do not forget
         to click 'Save'.  This will save the window position also, unless
         you have the 'Centre' option selected.

 @{"-> AutoStart Function" Link u-ats}

@endnode
@node u-ats "LChecker 2.1 Amigaguide Document"

   Read this section carefully before setting the AutoStart functions.  The
AutoStart function allows you to automatically start LChecker at the beginning of
your Startup-Sequence, so you don't have to wait around for your computer to bootup
before checking your numbers.

   In order to use the AutoStart function, you must modify your Startup-Sequence.
The following line is best placed early on in the Startup-Sequence, but you must
make sure that ENV: and ENVARC: are set up before it is run:

   @{b}<LCPath>/LChecker2.1@{ub}

   DO NOT start it with a 'Run >nil:', or the Startup-Sequence will just carry on
while you are checking your numbers.  Could cause problems...?!
   If you use SysPic or similar, then run LC before that.

   Okay then, now all you have to do is set the Tooltypes.  Simply activate the
days when you want LC to AutoStart (eg: 'SATURDAY' and 'WEDNESDAY'), and then set
the time IN 24 HOUR FORMAT WITH NO COLON ETC. that you want LC to start after.
   Confused?  Okay, some examples:-

   Lets say that you set the 'SATURDAY' Tooltype at '1955' (ie: 7:55pm).  Now,

   Day: Friday.........................................LChecker DOES NOT start.
   Day: Saturday  BootupTime: 7:35pm...................LChecker DOES NOT start.
   Day: Saturday  BootupTime: 8:05pm...................LChecker STARTS.
After this bootup, you then reboot again:
   Day: Saturday  BootupTime: 8:15pm...................LChecker DOES NOT start.

   There are three conditions to this working properly:
      1: Do NOT touch 'ENV:LCRan'
      2: Do NOT touch 'ENVARC:LCDone'
      3: You don't boot up your computer on Saturday at 8:05 (for example) and
         then only boot again next Saturday after 7:55pm.  In this case LC will
         not AutoStart.  But what are the chances of that happening?!!

   The AutoStart function is good in that it won't AutoStart if the day is not
the same as any of the set Tooltypes, or if the time is less than the value of
the day's tooltype.  However, after bootup you can still start LC manually,
without problems.
   If there is a bug in LChecker, it will probably be in this function, so please
report any problems that you find.  Give precise details or I may not be able to
help!  Of course, maybe I'll be lucky and it will work fine...
   Please try it out, it won't wreck your HD or anything...?! :)

 @{"-> Keyboard Shortcuts" Link u-kbs}

@endnode
@node u-kbs "LChecker 2.1 Amigaguide Document"

   Here is a list of available Keyboard shortcuts.  It does not include those for
the Menus.  You can see those for yourself!

   [SPACE]........Switch between 'Check' and 'Alter' modes.

   [UP]...........Scroll up a row.
   [DOWN].........Scroll down a row.
   [LEFT].........Move 'Current Row' marker up.
   [RIGHT]........Move 'Current Row' marker down.

   [1]->[5].......Jump straight to rows 1,11,21,31,41.

 @{"->   Tooltypes List  " Link u-ttl}

@endnode
@node u-ttl "LChecker 2.1 Amigaguide Document"

   And now for a list of available tooltypes:-

   WORKBENCH:  Workbench or Custom screen?
   CENTRE:     Centre LChecker's window?
   WINX=?:     X-Position of LChecker's window.
   WINY=?:     Y-Position of LChecker's window.
   FASTQUIT:   Confirm before quitting?

   MONDAY=?
    ....
   SUNDAY=?:   @{"AutoStart" Link u-ats} settings.

   ROW01=?
    ...
   ROW50=?:    Stores your Lottery Numbers.

 @{"->   Error Messages  " Link u-erm}
@endnode
@node u-erm "LChecker 2.1 Amigaguide Document"

   A list of error messages for your viewing pleasure:-

   'Unable To Locate LChecker's Icon'.......LC needs a .info to store Tooltypes.

   'Unable To Locate LC2.S'.................Keep this file in LC's drawer.

   'Workbench Screen To Small'..............Turn off the 'WORKBENCH' Tooltype.

@endnode
@node cop "LChecker 2.1 Amigaguide Document"

   The LChecker archive contains the files LChecker2.1, LChecker2.1.info, LC2.S
and LChecker.guide (this text).  The collective term 'LChecker' in the statement
below refers to all of these files.

   LChecker is ©1997 Richard Martin.  It may be freely distributed, provided
that no fee is charged, above a reasonable amount to cover the costs of media
and distribution.  This should be comparable to the price of an Aminet CD, for
a CD distribution, or should be no more than Ł1.50 for a floppy disk based
distribution.
   LChecker may be distrubuted on a magazine cover-media, but I would like to
be informed of this in writing.  A free copy of the magazine would be much
appreciated.  'Amiga Format' is exempt from the previous request.
   No part of LChecker may be changed or decompiled in any way, with the single
exception of LChecker.guide.  I would be grateful to anyone who translates this
file into a different language, provided that it is translated accurately, and
without changes to the content, other than the addition of a note stating that
they translated the file.  If you send the file to me then I will distribute it
with future versions of the LChecker program.
   All parts of LChecker must be distributed together, with no exceptions.

   LChecker is GIFTWARE.  If you use LChecker regularly and find it useful, then
please send a gift of your choice to me, for example a chocoalte bar, money :),
piece of software you have written, zip-drive, modem ;) etc...  Thankyou!

 @{"->  Disclaimer " Link dis}
@endnode
