@node opn "LChecker 2.1 Amigaguide Document"

   Well, here are a few topics and my opinions on them.  Feel free to take a look.
You may well disagree with what I say, but I don't care! :)  These are just my
humble opinions, not a statement from God!

 @{" GateWay2000 " Link o-gw2}....A bright future?
 @{"Escom/Viscorp" Link o-esv}....#?>&*%Ł!!!
 @{"  Commodore  " Link o-com}....Were they a good thing?

 @{"NewIcons/M-WB" Link o-nim}....Which is best? (Surely it's obvious :)
 @{"     MUI     " Link o-mui}....Saviour or Spawn of Satan?

 @{" AmigaOS 4.0 " Link o-aos}....What do _I_ think should go in it?
 @{" Phase 5 PPC " Link o-ppc}....The future?

@endnode
@node o-gw2 "LChecker 2.1 Amigaguide Document"

   Well I have to agree with those people at Amiga Format here.  I think that, at
first, GW2K seem very quiet about the Amiga, but that does seem like a good sign,
considering the way that Escom/Viscorp boasted about what they were going to do.
At least we have seen the forming of a dedicated 'Amiga Inc.' side company, and
we are now hearing about...no wait, surely it's not true...Research and
Development.  R-e-s-e-a-r-c-h-!-!  On the Amiga!!
   And, of course, Mr Petro Tstchenko (erm...not spelled like that I think :) is
staying on as head of Amiga Inc.  That can only be a good thing.
   So, basically, I am confident that the Amiga is in good hands.
@endnode
@node o-esv "LChecker 2.1 Amigaguide Document"

   One down, one to go!  That's basically what I feel.  Escom, it seems, were
only after the C= logo, while Viscorp were mostly interested in grabbing the
technology needed for their Set-Top Boxes.  Escom have now sunk without trace,
and it would be nice if Viscorp do the same.  The only nice thing I can say about
the company is that they might create some business for Amiga Inc.!!
   Oh, of course, how could I forget.  Escom did take the Amiga giant leaps
forward when they created.....'The Walker'!  Oh, if only that had have gone on
sale to the public, the Amiga's reputation would have been safe forever!  Or, 
maybe not.  And who can fault the amazing work done by the staff at Escom shops!
Let's see now, what was it?  Ah, yes..." On no, you don't want to buy an Amiga!!
Try this PC instead, they're much better."  Such incredible sales tactics!
   Rot in hell, Escom!
@endnode
@node o-com "LChecker 2.1 Amigaguide Document"

   Maybe I'm just a bit too nice, but I will always have a soft spot for good old
Commodore.  Yes, they did make some HUGE mistakes at the end, but that was because
their tactics had worked so well with the A500, 10 years before.  It is all too
easy to judge after the event, but Commodore can't be blamed too much, for not
realising the change in the industry.  They were stupid and blind, yes, but at
least they did _want_ the Amiga to do well.
   Don't misunderstand me, I am glad to be rid of them now, but without Commodore
the Amiga would have been raised by Atari (Ugh!), or may well have not got of the
ground due to lack of cash.  So, thanks Commodore, but I hope that reincarnation
doesn't apply to companies!! :)
@endnode
@node o-nim "LChecker 2.1 Amigaguide Document"

   Why, why, why, why, why, why?!  Why do people continue to believe that the MWB
icon collection is better than the NewIcons system?  Okay, let's go through
things step by step!

   NewIcons - 16/32(v4) colour standard.  MWB - 8 colour standard.
   
   NewIcons - upto 256 user selectable colours.  MWB - 8 pre-defined colours.

   NewIcons - Proper RAM icon solution.  MWB - Bit of CLI code soloution.

   NewIcons - Borderless/Tranparency options.  MWB - Nope!

   NewIcons - RTG option to save ChipRAM.  MWB - Yeah, right!

   NewIcons - Comes with great DefIcons tool.  MWB - Just icons.

   NewIcons - Colour remapping (OS3.0).  MWB - Fixed palette only.

   NewIcons - Erm...Oh yes.  It's >FREE<!  MWB - Ł15 + Ł8 per update!!!!!!!

   So what has MWB got?  Erm...it uses less ChipRAM, but if you have a GFX card
then you can use the RTG function anyway.  And NewIcons can take a bit of time to
decompress, but if you have an '030 then there is _very_ little difference.
   No, I'm sorry, but NewIcons is definitely the way forward...
@endnode
@node o-mui "LChecker 2.1 Amigaguide Document"

   Why, why, why, etc...  What is wrong with this great piece of software?  So
you need a bit of memory to use it!  How much is a 4MB RAM card?  I got 8MB
for under Ł50, and prices are falling.  For this, you get a great looking
interface for MUI programs, and programmers can spend more time on the program
because of less time spent making a GUI.  You also get automatic Font-Sensitivity
and Window-Resizing in every MUI program!  Register, and you, the user, can
customise your MUI software to your hearts content.
   MUI is a great program, which should be incorporated into OS 4.0.  And, against
what many MUI-Haters claim, it _IS_ part of what the Amiga stands for:  Taking
control from the big companies and handing it back to the users.
   I know this:  LChecker would have been much easier to create if I could have
incorporated MUI into Blitz!!
@endnode
@node o-aos "LChecker 2.1 Amigaguide Document"

   Well, MUI for a start :).  Really, I think that DOpus, MUI, NewIcons,
MagicMenu and KingCON make a great Workbench, but thhere are a couple of things
missing.  For starters it needs more standards.  We do have things like AHI, RTG,
NewIcons/MWB(?;), but none of it is _official_.  Gateway2000 need to talk to the
Authors of these types of software and arrange deals with them.  The problem is
that all of these not-quite-standards often causes slight problems with the
system because they are not geared to work together.  Eg: NewIcons and DOpus5.5
both 'fight' to remap my icons, so I sometimes get odd colour schemes.  None of
the problems are major ones, or not workaroundable, but they do detract from the
'profesional' feeling that an OS should have.
   In WB 4.0 I think that _everything_ should be user-configurable, preferably
from one big Preferences program, by the use of pages etc.  I also think that a
'modular' WB should be considered.  Let me explain:  Instead of having the menu
system built securely into the OS, you should have a separate 'module' that you
could remove and replace with a, 100% system friendly, module programmed by
someone else, eg: the lasted MMenu!  This would vastly reduce the number of hacks
on your system, thereby reducing clashes, crashes, etc. and making life better
for everyone.  There would, obviously, be losses in speed and compactness, but I
believe that it could well be worth it...!
   One thing that I _really_ believe in, is that GW2K should not go Gates and
charge people for writing stuff for their OS.  This may make some extra money,
but it would kill the 'essence' of the Amiga.  It is only survived this far due
to the Shareware scene and such a policy would kill off the Amiga's best asset.
No, keep the Amiga free and original.  Otherwise, it may as well be dead!
@endnode
@node o-ppc "LChecker 2.1 Amigaguide Document"

   Yes!  Phase 5 seem to be doing a great deal of work on their ABox thingy, and
it looks set to be a machine that takes the Amiga beyond the realms of the PC.
There's not much that I can say, other than I think that Phase 5 should be
encouraged as much as possible with their new Amiga.  That's it!
@endnode
@node bug "LChecker 2.1 Amigaguide Document"

   There are two known problems for LChecker, but I think that both of them are
problems with Blitz Basic, because I have scanned my code several times, and
simply cannot locate the problem.

   1: When you re-open LC's window, eg:after changing screens, if you do not have
      the 'Centre' funtion on, then the window shifts down and to the right...?!

   2: Not a bug as such, but I have had to use non-standard menu's, because I
      could not get the GTMenu.library of the Blitz Support Suite to work
      properly!  Does anyone else have this problem?  Is there a solution?!

   As for improvements, the main thing that I want to do is separate the
AutoStart function from the main code, so that it won't delay your Startup-Sequence
for as long (although it is only a matter of ~2 seconds now).  Also, I may learn
C in the future, so look out for a re-write.....

